commitResults.messageTitle: fix: change unique parameter of persons in the addressbook to email
commitResults.messageBody:
initially the unique parameter of persons in the addressbook was the
name of the person. however, it does not make sense for the name of
the person to be unique as it is not uncommon for 2 persons in the
cohort to have the same name. therefore, we changed the unique parameter
to the email address of persons as 2 students in a cohort should not
have the same email address.

change,
* method in Person class that compares two persons if they are equal
to compare the email address of the persons instead of the name
* error message of the addressbook to warn users of a duplicate email
address in a contact they attempt to add

commitResults.messageTitle: fix: change email address comparison to be case insensitive
commitResults.messageBody:
email addresses are case insensitive. this means that email@gmail.com
is the same as EMAIL@gmail.com.

edit equals method in Email class to ignore case when comparing email
addresses

source:https://mailchimp.com/resources/are-email-addresses-case-sensitiv
e/#:~:text=As%20mentioned%20earlier%2C%20capital%20letters,correctly%2C%
20it%20will%20work%20properly.

commitResults.messageTitle: fix: edit tests involving testing for same persons
commitResults.messageBody:
since the unique parameter that identifies a person is changed to email
address of a person, the test cases which test for the same persons
should be changed.

changes,
* test cases testing for persons with the same email with all other
attributes different should return true for the boolean method
isSamePerson
* test cases testing for persons with the different email with all other
attributes same should return false for the boolean method
isSamePerson
* test cases testing for same email address but with different letter
casing should return true as email is case-insensitive

The only way to obtain the emails of people in the list is to manually
copy them one by one.

This is not ideal as a large list would take a proportionately long
time to obtain all the emails.

As such, lets implement the copy command to follow the behavior
suggested in the developer guide, copying all emails currently listed
in the last shown list. The command would take into consideration if the
latest list is empty, and notifies the user if there are no emails to
be copied. If the list is empty, the emails of all persons displayed
would be copied into the user's clipboard. The user can then paste this
anywhere using `ctrl+v`.

This command has been implemented to meet the identified needs of our
target users to aid in quickening communication between the user and
target groups.

This commit will also include all relevant tests to ensure that
the methods involved have been thoroughly tested.

commitResults.messageTitle: Bug fix: Run in headless mode
commitResults.messageBody:
The key reason why the test case fails the GitHub checks is because
the copy command relies on copying information to a keyboard. Since the
checks are done in headless mode, java.awt.HeadlessException will be
thrown. Hence the copy command will only copy to the clipboard if
it is in headed mode to avoid this issue.
Remove unused imports to improve code quality.
Changed the order of the imports to adhere to coding standards.

Changed the structure of the code to isolate all awt code that
requires headed mode such that the code can be covered by unit testing.
The testcases have been altered accordingly.

This ensures code coverage whilst keeping the functionality of the
command the same.
